			<td colspan="6" class="DetailTitle" style="text-align:center;">
                            Summary on Grant Application Form</td>
		</tr>
		<tr>
			<td colspan="6" class="DetailValue" style="padding:5px;">
                        <span id="lblAbstract">This proposal is for a 7 month visit to a laboratory in France concerned with the digital processing of signals and images (Laboratoire des Images et des Signaux - LIS). The PI works in the field of colour image processing and has a current cooperation with LIS in the field of processing vector signals using linear algebra techniques based on quaternions. Vector signals occur in seismic signal processing, where air blasts or explosions are used to send sound waves into the ground or seabed. The echoes of these waves can be picked up and processed to find out what is under the ground - layers of rock of different types, or oil or gas. If the signals are detected using three-dimensional vector sensors that can separate vibrations in three different directions, information about the waves includes polarisation, that is the direction and manner in which the wave vibrated in the rock. Colour images have three digital values at each pixel location, one each for the red, green and blue components. Therefore processing of vector seismic signals is similar mathematically to processing of colour images, as is done in digital image manipulation or in computer analysis of colour images.Processing techniques for signals and images with three components per sample or pixel are relatively undeveloped and this research continues a collaboration based on the use of quaternions and quaternion algebra. Quaternions are hypercomplex numbers with four components, that is they are similar to complex numbers which have two components, but in the case of quaternions, there are three imaginary components and one real component. Quaternions are closely related to vectors in three dimensions, indeed the imaginary part of a quaternion number is a vector. Vectors express direction and magnitude in three dimensional space, and they can therefore represent colour image pixels (the three dimensional space is RGB colour space), or they can represent vibrations in real three-dimensional space within rock, which is essentially what vector seismic signals are representing.The particular research to be conducted during a visit to LIS concerns the use of the quaternionic singular value decomposition (QSVD) and related algorithms. The QSVD is a linear algebra technique, that is, it applies to matrices, in this case, matrices of quaternions, which represent either a seismic signal or a colour image. Computing the QSVD takes a lot of computer time, and since it was published in 1997, the most common way to calculate it was by using two complex number QSVDs. The PI and his colleague in Grenoble (Dr le Bihan) have already shown how to compute the QSVD directly using quaternion algebra, but the method is not very fast. They propose to develop a much faster method and then use it to explore how the QSVD can be used. A closely related technique, quaternion independent component analysis (QICA) allows a signal or image to be separated into independent components, allowing these components to be processed and analysed.</span>
                        </td>
		</tr>
